<p><b>1. Recognition</b> techniques for passers by (detecting their sex, age, etc.) and choosing the most relevant advertising poster to show to a particular kind of person. Traffic analysis.</p>
<p>This kind of targeting (instead of a trivial periodical switch) can be implemented using long-existing face recognition algorithms, and it's not too difficult to develop one's own. OpenCV makes it easy (for example, <a href="http://face.com">face.com</a> uses these technologies).</p>
<p>Examples: when a middle-aged woman walks past a billboard, the system selects a perfume ad. When there's a young man, the system chooses to show him Nike sneakers.</p>
<p>Challenges: there should be some additional adjustment when there's a flow of people passing by, not just a single person. Perhaps the algorithm should adapt the strategy according to the largest group or select the most "important" ad.</p>
<p>One can collect some useful statistics for each board, for instance, how many people have passed by, how many of them have looked at the advertising, and who exactly has done it.</p>
<p>It is important to understand that such a thing is rather to be used in the areas with an average traffic, because a huge billboard would "see" a lot of people and traffic is uniform almost all the time, so the benefits of targeting would be reduced to zero.</p>
