<p><b>2.</b> Working with an angle of view (<b>perspective view</b>).</p>
<p>All the modern screens can show a picture without any angle and perspective distortions. Here's an <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BduSDvUU6MY&feature=youtu.be">example</a> of binding an image on the screen to the view vector. So this way one can create a virtual 3D space behind the screen and display images without angular distortion.</p>
<p>Back to our billboard screen, if a person walks past the screen, the image will always appear with a correct height to width ratio. This is an interesting and quite attractive effect, which draws attention to the ad. The angle of view can be easily obtained by using the recognition techniques from the paragraph 1.</p>
<p>Challenges: this would work only for one view vector, so people in all other positions would see more or less distorted picture. But anyway people see distorted images almost all the time, this technique just gives an opportunity to improve it in some cases.</p>
--
<p><b>3. Interaction.</b></p>
<p>Knowing the observer's position and creating a virtual 3D space behind the screen for him/her, one can create a very interesting interactive scenes, including advertising ones.</p>
<p>Example: a young man walks past the screen, the system detects the position of his face and draws a 3D scene for the corresponding view vector. A young man sees behind the screen a virtual continuation of the real space without distortions. The virtual scene contains a basketball player with a ball, who's looking at the young man (because the system knows the relative position of the viewer and can calculate where the baller should look), sound of the the bouncing ball can be heard. It looks like it's just the glass behind which there is a basketball player. He raises his hand and points to the "spectator", throws the ball into the screen... Sound of collision with glass. Logo. Wow effect.</p>
<p>Problems: again, this works works for one vector, and creating a correct perspective is possible only for one person (well, there would be some minor distortions for those who stand next to that one).</p>
<p>Creating an animated scene is very simple, it's not much more expensive than a movie, but it would be interactive with the audience, which brings it to a completely different level.</p>
